Question 2

Column

  1. An estimate of the number and percentage of K-12 students who have no internet access at home, using the latest available PUMS data. (Note that 2019 1-yr PUMS data will be available in mid-October 2020, so you might choose to update your analysis using that data at that time.) State your assumptions clearly, especially how useful the available data is for understanding the challenges of remote learning in 2020. Include a map of this metric for all PUMAs in the Bay Area.

Interpretation: The areas with the highest percentage of households with K-12 kids with no internet access are around Alameda while the lowest percent of households who have kids with no internet access are around San Francisco and San Jose. Assumptions: We only take into account people who filled out the census. We look at it on the household level rather than an individual level , meaning that a house could have multiple kids with no internet access residing within it, yet that would only count as 1 rather than for each kid. This means that bigger families are less likely to be accurately portrayed. We are assuming kids are K-12 if they are under the age of 17 thus, highschool kids over the age of 17 are not being represented
